===============these are some common foods that can cause allergies and there symptoms==================


Peanuts
	Symptoms: Skin reactions like hives, redness, or swelling, digestive discomfort, tightening of the throat, shortness of breath, and anaphylaxis.

Tree Nuts (e.g., walnuts, almonds, cashews, pistachios)
	Symptoms: Similar to peanut allergies, including abdominal pain, cramps, nausea, vomiting, difficulty swallowing, and anaphylaxis.

Milk (Cow's milk is most common)
        Symptoms: Hives, vomiting, digestive problems, and can cause anaphylaxis in severe cases. Often confused with lactose intolerance, which is different as it's a reaction to sugar in milk rather than the protein.

Eggs
        Symptoms: Skin reactions, respiratory problems, stomach pain, and in rare cases, anaphylaxis.

Fish
        Symptoms: Hives, nausea, headaches, anaphylaxis, and asthma-like symptoms such as breathing difficulties.

Shellfish (e.g., shrimp, prawns, lobster, crab)
        Symptoms: Vomiting, diarrhea, stomach pain, indigestion, wheezing, repetitive cough, tightness in throat, shock or circulatory collapse, dizziness, and weak pulse.

Wheat
        Symptoms: Swelling or irritation of the mouth and throat, hives, nasal congestion, headaches, difficulty breathing, cramps, nausea, or anaphylaxis.

Soy
	Symptoms: Itching, tingling in the mouth, swelling of face, throat, or other body parts, skin redness, breathing difficulty (including wheezing), and anaphylaxis in severe cases.

Sesame
        Symptoms: One of the newer allergens recognized in various regions, symptoms include hives, dizziness, nausea, abdominal pain, and anaphylaxis.


================================these are some common symptoms that person is having the food allergy==============

feeling dizzy or lightheaded
itchy skin or a raised rash (hives)
swelling of the lips, face and eyes (angioedema)
coughing, wheezing, breathlessness, noisy breathing or a hoarse voice
sneezing or an itchy, runny or blocked nose
feeling sick or being sick
tummy pain
diarrhoea
Dermatological: Redness, hives, eczema, swelling of the lips, face, and eyes.
Gastrointestinal: Nausea, abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhea.
Respiratory: Sneezing, wheezing, throat tightness, coughing, and nasal congestion.
Cardiovascular: Drop in blood pressure, fast pulse, fainting, anaphylactic shock.
Tingling or itching in the mouth.
Hives, itching or eczema.
Swelling of the lips, face, tongue, and throat or other parts of the body.
Wheezing, nasal congestion or trouble breathing.
Belly pain, diarrhea, nausea or vomiting.
Dizziness, lightheadedness or fainting.
Constriction and tightening of the airways.
A swollen throat or the sensation of a lump in your throat that makes it hard to breathe.
Shock with a severe drop in blood pressure.
Rapid pulse.
Dizziness, lightheadedness or loss of consciousness.
Hives or skin rash.
Swelling of the lips or eyelids.
Itching mouth and throat, tongue swelling.
Hoarse voice, difficulty swallowing.
Cough, wheezing or shortness of breath.
Abdominal pain, vomiting , diarrhea.
Lightheadedness or loss of consciousness.

Vomiting and/or stomach cramps
Hives
Shortness of breath
Wheezing
Repetitive cough
Shock or circulatory collapse
Tight, hoarse throat; trouble swallowing
Swelling of the tongue, affecting the ability to talk or breathe
Weak pulse
Pale or blue coloring of skin
Dizziness or feeling faint
Anaphylaxis, a potentially life-threatening reaction that can impair breathing and send the body into shock; reactions may simultaneously affect different parts of the body (for example, a stomachache accompanied by a rash)



